\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Economic growth is a very important concept in macroeconomics.
 It can be defined as the increase or improvement in the inflation-adjusted
 market value of the goods and services produced by an economy (also known
 as 
\shape italic
GDP
\shape default
) over a certain period of time.
 Since high economic growth would generally make a nation more prosperous,
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
When we say high economic growth here, we are referring strictly to the
 amount of growth within an economy's capacity.
 When the economic growth is too rapid, the economy will start to 
\shape italic

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

overheat
\shape default
 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which will cause high rate of inflation, among many other undesirable
 effects
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which in turn would generally improve its citizens' standards of living.
 It is for this reason that in the modern history, increasing the rate of
 economic growth is almost the universal preoccupation of almost every country's
 government regardless of the form of governance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the rate of economic growth can vary quite widely from one year
 to the other, which poses a problem for government planning.
 Therefore, if we can predict the rate of economic growth, it would be undoubted
ly helpful for the government in terms of planning its government expenditure,
 taxation, etc.
 Currently, one of the most classic models that is used to predict long-run
 economic growth is the 
\series bold
Solow‚ÄìSwan model
\series default
 or 
\series bold
exogenous growth model.
 
\series default
Mathematically, this is an nonlinear system consisting of a single ordinary
 differential equation that models the evolution of the per capita stock
 of capital.
 In the following sections, I will firstly introduce the model before going
 on to explore the nonlinear dynamics of the system for two different versions
 of the model (with increasing complexity)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Here, it is important to keep in mind that the versions of model explored
 would not be exhaustive
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as well as trying to compare the model to some real-world data that I was
 able to collect online.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Solow-Swan model with AK technology and constant labour growth rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is worth mentioning before we go any further that we are measuring the
 rate of economic growth by rate of capital accumulation here.
 It is important to note that these two concepts are not the same yet they
 are still deeply connected in the sense that the accumulation of capital
 goods translates to investment and the production of more goods and services,
 which should boost the income of the population and stimulate demand.
 (In the other words, economic growth) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This version of the model is arguably the most basic form of the model,
 but it will serve as a basis for our investigation going forward.
 This version of the model is set up based on the following assumptions/conditio
ns:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Tbere is one good (
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}$
\end_inset

) produced by only one factor of production (
\begin_inset Formula $K_{t}$
\end_inset

).
 Therefore the resulting production function is 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}=F(K_{t})=AK_{t}$
\end_inset

, where A is an exogenous positive constant that represents the level of
 technology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Saving is proportional to the aggregate income i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{t}=sY_{t}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 denotes the exogeneous saving rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Since the economy is closed, the change in the capital stock could be represente
d as 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $K_{t}\prime$
\end_inset

