\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $K_{t}\prime=sY_{t}-ùõøK_{t}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $ùõø$
\end_inset

 is the rate of depreciation 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In the context of the model, we consider population = labour.
 That is to say that 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\frac{L\prime_{t}}{L_{t}}$
\end_inset

, the constant population growth rate would equate to labour growth rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we are more interested in per-capita terms, we define a new variable
 called the 
\series bold
capital-labour ratio
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}=\frac{K_{t}}{L_{t}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{k_{t}\prime}{k_{t}}=\frac{K_{t}\prime}{K_{t}}-\frac{L_{t}\prime}{L_{t}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then by some simple calculations that I would omit here, we get: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{t}\prime=(N-n)k_{t},N\equiv sA-ùõø
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This first order differential equation in 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the fundamental equation of the Solow-Swan model with a production function
 which is linear in physical capital.
 From this equation, we can plot the evolution of the capital of stock with
 respect to time as shown in Figure 1 when the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $(N-n)$
\end_inset

 takes different signs.
 We can notice that: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For 
\begin_inset Formula $N=n$
\end_inset

, regardless the initial condition, steady state has
\series bold
 zero growth
\series default
 in per-worker capital stock
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For 
\begin_inset Formula $N<n$
\end_inset

, we notice negative growth throughout, and the economy will converge in
 the long-run to a per-worker capital stock equal to zero
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For 
\begin_inset Formula $N>n,$
\end_inset

we notice positive growth throughout, and the economy will approach an infinitel
y large level of per-worker capital stock in the long run
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Obviously, the third senario will be the most favourable for an economy.
 When we translate the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $N>n$
\end_inset

 into plain english, it will state that the savings rate (adjusted by the
