\begin_layout Section
The Solow-Swan model with AK technology and logistic labour growth rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we are going to be modifying the model for population growth
 to complicate things a little bit.
 The problem that we had with constant labour growth rate before is that
 population would grow exponentially without any constraint.
 Namely, the solution to 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\frac{L\prime_{t}}{L_{t}}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{t}=L_{0}*e^{nt}$
\end_inset

.
 Obviously, this model of population growth would not be realistic, which
 is the reason why we are introducing the logistic equation for labour/populatio
n growth:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This population growth model is discussed in depth at Page 22 in Strogatz.
 To save the repetitiveness, I will just summarize the results here.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{L_{t}\prime}{L_{t}}=n-bL_{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is population growth rate as usual, 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is a constant satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $n-bL_{t}>0$
\end_inset

.
 This equation can also be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{L_{t}\prime}{L_{t}}=n(1-\frac{L_{t}}{ùêä})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $ùêä$
\end_inset

 denotes 
\series bold
carrying capacity
\series default
.
 (i.e., the maximum population size of a biological species that can be sustained
 by that specific environment.) Instead of solving this differential equation
 analytically, we plot 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{t}\prime$
\end_inset

 against 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{t}$
\end_inset

 like we have done many times as shown in Figure 2.
\series bold

