This figure shows that no matter where the population starts from, the populatio
n converges eventually to the carry capacity as t goes to infinity.
 (In the other words, K in the graph is a stable fixed point.) Therefore,
 incorporating the symbols and equations that we have introduced a bit earlier,
 we get the following system of equation to represent the AK technology
 model with logistic labour growth rate: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
k_{t}\prime & =\left[N-(n-bL_{t})\right]k_{t}\\
L_{t}\prime & =L_{t}(n-bL_{t})
\end{cases}(*)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where if we are given the initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $(k_{0}>0,L_{0}>0)$
\end_inset

 we can get a unique solution 
\begin_inset Formula $(k_{t},L_{t})$
\end_inset

.
 In the next section, we are going to investigate the steady state (see
 the definition a bit later) and some of the dynamics of the model after
 we made the switch to the logistic labour growth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Steady state and dynamics of model with logistic labour growth rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start off by defining what is the steady state of the model.
 A steady state in an economy refers to the situation where the growth of
 population/labour and per capita physical capital are both zero.
 After reading this definition, it is natural to make a connection with
 something we learned early on in class.
 And yes indeed, steady state in this context is just a fancier name for
 fixed point of two-dimension system.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For more detailed discussion on this, please refer to Section 6.3 in Strogatz.
\end_layout

\end_inset

We denote the steady state values of this system as 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{*}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{*}$
\end_inset

.
 From the first glance, it is evident that 
\begin_inset Formula $(k_{t},L_{t})=(0,0)$
\end_inset

 is always a fixed point.
 However, in this context, we will 
\series bold
disregard
\series default
 this solution as this is economically meaningless.
 After all, who would like to study the dynamics of an economy that has
 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 workers in it ? We would probably be better off spending our time elsewhere.
 After excluding this not-so-exciting solution, we have another pair of
 solution that satisfies: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
Nk_{t} & =0\\
n-bL_{t} & =0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving this system of the equation, we see that if 
\begin_inset Formula $N\neq0$
\end_inset

, we wouldn't obtain any non-trivial steady state as the only way to satisfy
 the first equation is to make 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}=0$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, we see that if 
\begin_inset Formula $N=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}$
\end_inset

 can take on any value to satisfy the first equation and along with 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{t}=\frac{n}{b}$
\end_inset

, a non-trivial fixed point could be obtained.
 To summarize, the economy has 
\series bold
no
\series default
 steady state when 
\begin_inset Formula $N\neq0$
\end_inset

 and has 
\series bold
infinite
\series default
 stead state when 
\begin_inset Formula $N=0$
\end_inset

.
 Now, the legitimate question that we can ask ourselves is that what kind
 of fixed point do we have when 
\begin_inset Formula $N\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 To find out, we employ linearization: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\frac{dk_{t}'}{dk_{t}} & \frac{dk_{t}'}{dL_{t}}\\
\frac{dL_{t}'}{dk_{t}} & \frac{dL_{t}'}{dL_{t}}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
N-n+bL_{t} & bk_{t}\\
0 & n-2bL_{t}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
N & bk_{t}\\
0 & -n
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

To look for the eigenvalue, set the determinant to zero at the fixed point
 
\begin_inset Formula $(k_{t},L_{t}=\frac{n}{b})$
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
det\left[\begin{array}{cc}
N-\lambda & bk_{t}\\
0 & -n-\lambda
\end{array}\right]=0
\]

\end_inset

which gives: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(N-\lambda)(-n-\lambda)=0;(N-\lambda)(n+\lambda)=0
\]

\end_inset

Then, we have two eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}=N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}=-n$
\end_inset

.
 In the other word, depending on the signs of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-n$
\end_inset

, we will have either saddle, unstable, stable node locally around the steady
 state (fixed point).
 These are all hyperbolic points, so according to the 
\shape italic
Hartman-Grobman Theory
\shape default
 
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For more detailed discussion on this, please refer to page 156 in Strogatz.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, our use of linearization to determine the stability of steady state is
 justified.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\shape italic
Remark
\shape default
: Even though theoretically we can take any value for the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(N,n)$
\end_inset

 as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $N\neq0$
\end_inset

, we would typically want to take both as positive in reality.
 If one recalls the definition from an earlier section, the variable 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 represents population/labour growth rate, which has the range 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\frac{L_{t}'}{L_{t}}\leq n-bL_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 This range confirms what we are observing in the real world.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For more intuitive discussion on this claim, please read 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "this"
target "https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/global-population-growth-is-slowing-down-heres-one-reason-why/"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 excellent article by the scientific american.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 With this observation, this fixed point would be either a stable node or
 saddle point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From system 
\begin_inset Formula $(*)$
\end_inset

 from the last section, we can solve for the explicit expression of 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{t}=k_{0}e^{\intop_{0}^{t}(N-\frac{L_{t}'}{L_{t}})dt}=\frac{k_{0}L_{0}e^{Nt}}{L_{t}}(**)
\]

\end_inset

 However, from the equation we got under the expoential population growth
 rate assumption: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{t}\prime=(N-n)k_{t}
\]

\end_inset

We can also solve 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}$
\end_inset

 to have the same expression as 
\begin_inset Formula $(**)$
\end_inset

.
 That is an interesting observation, meaning that even under our new population
 growth assumption, the path of per-worker capital is still the same.
 In particular, given the positive initial condition 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{0}>0;L_{0}>0$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}$
\end_inset

 negatively on the population/labour size 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{t}$
\end_inset

 at time t.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
That conclusion is fairly intuitive when we draw an analogy with dissolving
 some fixed amount of particle in increasing larger quantity of solutions
 (dilution).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Figure 3 does a good job illustrating the time path of the population growth
 under logistic model.
 
