\end_inset

We finish this section can make some simple observations on the relationship
 between the economic growth (
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{k_{t}'}{k_{t}})$
\end_inset

 and net adjusted saving rate (N).
 For simplicity define 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{k_{t}'}{k_{t}}\equiv\gamma_{k_{t}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{L_{t}'}{L_{t}}\equiv\gamma_{L_{t}}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that we have the following from the first equation of the system(*):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{t}\prime=\left[N-(n-bL_{t})\right]k_{t}=[N-\frac{L_{t}'}{L_{t}}]k_{t}=[N-\gamma_{L_{t}}]k_{t}
\]

\end_inset

Rearranging terms to get: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\gamma_{k_{t}}=N-\gamma_{L_{t}}
\]

\end_inset

With this we have the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $N=0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{k_{t}}=-\gamma_{L_{t}}<0$
\end_inset

.
 The last inequality sign is from the range that is given earlier in the
 section.
 Therefore, if 
\begin_inset Formula $N=0$
\end_inset

, we will have negative economic growth.
 However, as 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, economic growth would tend to zero.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We can see from Figure 3 shown above that the population growth tends to
 flatten out.
 In the context of logistic population growth model, this happens when the
 population of a territory/habiat reaches the carry capacity K.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $N<0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{k_{t}}=N-\gamma_{L_{t}}<0$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, if 
\begin_inset Formula $N<0$
\end_inset

, we will also have negative economic growth.
 However, as 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, economic growth would stay negative.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $N\geq n-bL_{0}>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{k_{t}}\geq0$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $t\geq0$
\end_inset

 .
 Therefore, in this situation, we will have positive economic growth.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Solow growth model in real life
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With all these above being said, one might want very naturally that whether
 the economic growth in the real life can be predicted to some degree of
 accuracy by the basic Solow model described above.
 That is precisely what we are going to investigate in this section.
 From the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $(**)$
\end_inset

 that we obtained in the previous section, we see that the value 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}$
\end_inset

 will increase as the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

 increases.
 However, as 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}\equiv sA-ùõø$
\end_inset

, we can derive that the value 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}$
\end_inset

 increases as saving's rate (
\begin_inset Formula $s)$
\end_inset

 increases.
 In the same expression, we also see that as the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{t}$
\end_inset

 increases, the value 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}$
\end_inset

 would decrease.
 Equivalently, we can say that the value 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{t}$
\end_inset

 decreases as the population growth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 increases.
 Recall that at the very beginning, we assumed that we are using so-called
 
\series bold
AK Technology production function
\series default
 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}=F(K_{t})=AK_{t}$
\end_inset

).
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}$
\end_inset

 in this equation is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}$
\end_inset

 would also have the same relationship with respect to saving's rate (
\begin_inset Formula $s)$
\end_inset

 and population growth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $(n)$
\end_inset

.
 In summary: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Income 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}$
\end_inset

 (therefore income per capita) is 
\series bold
increasing
\series default
 in the saving's rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Income 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{t}$
\end_inset

 (therefore income per capita) is 
\series bold
decreasing
\series default
 in the population growth rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above two relationships given by the Solow model are what we are going
 to test on the real-life dataset.
 Before jumping into the testing, there is one remark to be made regarding
 to the saving's rate (
\begin_inset Formula $s)$
\end_inset

: due to the difficulties that I encountered in getting saving's rate 
\begin_inset Formula $(s)$
\end_inset

